walkthru=1

@jd:body


<p>That's it! Your Android SDK is ready for action. Here are a few ways you can get started: </p>

<p><strong>Start coding</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Follow the training class for <a
href="{@docRoot}training/basics/firstapp/index.html">Building Your First App</a>.
    <p>This class is an essential first step for new Android developers.</p>
    <p>It gives you step by step instructions for building a simple app. Youâ€™ll learn how to
create an Android project and run a debuggable version of the app. You'll also learn some
fundamentals of Android app design, including how to build a simple user interface and handle user
input.</p>
</li>
</ul>


<p><strong>Read up on the API framework</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Start reading about fundamental framework topics in the collection of <a
href="{@docRoot}guide/index.html">Guides</a>.</li>
  <li>Browse the Android API specifications in the <a
  href="{@docRoot}reference/packages.html">Reference</a>.</li>
</ul>


<p><strong>Explore the development tools</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Learn about the process for developing an app from end to end with the <a
  href="{@docRoot}tools/index.html">Workflow</a> documentation.</li>
  <li>Learn about debugging your apps with the <a
href="{@docRoot}tools/debugging/index.html">Debugging</a> guides.</li>
</ul>


<p><strong>Explore some code</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>Browse the sample apps downloaded from the Android SDK Manager. You'll find them in
<code><em>&lt;sdk&gt;</em>/samples/<em>&lt;platform-version&gt;/</em></code>. </li>
</ul>
